			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Greetings,
<br />

<br />
   Before spending money on programs that really don't do anything for you, I would recommend doing the following;
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Denaeb wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Where I hate it is when I visit a website and a program is downloaded onto my computer WITHOUT my consent that adds a pop up generating program to where anytime my computer is on will periodically display pop ups whether Im cruising the web or not (I have a cable modem).</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
   Stragenly enough, this has nothing to do with the websites.  IE does not allow applications to be downloaded and executed automatically unless it is a configuration utility to IE itself.   Instead to disable these non-web popups, simply got to:
<br />
 For Win2K
<br />
 Start >
<br />
 control panel >
<br />
 settings >
<br />
 messanger
<br />

<br />
 For XP
<br />
 Start >
<br />
 control panel >
<br />
 administrative tools >
<br />
 settings >
<br />
 messanger
<br />

<br />
   Change the start option from automatic to manual or disable and stop the service.  This will eliminate *ALL* non web based pop-ups.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I had one even that when I uninstalled it asked why I was uninstalling the program. Im thinking duh maybe its because I never asked for you shitty program and I could see no reason anyone would want a program like that on their computer.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
   Unfortunately you got caught by a malicious code bit here.  What really happened was that your system was sent a popup which asked you if you wanted to uninstall something.  By clicking yes, you were actually uninstalling something critical, most likely it was attempting to uninstall a security program like virus software or adware blockers.
<br />
 
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Honestly I think that kindof garbage should be illegal I can deal with straight popups but when its a forced prgram that I never wanted thats where I draw the line and anytime I visit a site that allows that type of immoral advertising I never ever visit it again.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
   Let ya in on a little secret here.  90% of these non-web based popups are being sent at the behest of the various computer security vendors.  The vendors themselves are not doing it, but they are aware that it is happening and allow it to happen to continue to sell their products.   If you read most of the popups closely they will have a link or a button that will take you to one of the security sites to buy the software to block the popups.
<br />

<br />
   Next, to block the majority of web based popups, simply uncheck the JIT in the IE advanced settings;
<br />
  tools > 
<br />
  internet options > 
<br />
  advanced >
<br />
  Microsoft VM >
<br />
  JIT
<br />

<br />
   Please note though that if you do this, there will be some sites that rely on java that will not function properly, though to be honest, those sites are few and far between.  Further, if you do this, you will occasionally get a popup from IE asking if you wish to enable this feature.
<br />

<br />
   Finally, many pages will have content that requires certain utilities to be installed into IE to view them, such as PDF readers or Flash readers.  When you hit these pages, occasionally, you will be asked if you wish to install the utility required to view these pages.  If you want to turn off this feature, simply uncheck the install on demand;
<br />
  tools > 
<br />
  internet options > 
<br />
  advanced >
<br />
  browsing >
<br />
  enable install on demand (other)
<br />

<br />
   Hope this helps.<br />_________________<br /><ul><li><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=67241">Elder Kaatt</a>, Sixty-Five Year Old Khati Sha Feral Lord of Xev.<li><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=337255">Investigator Aaeorn</a>, Fifty-Second Circle Redeemed Thief Catcher of Xev.<li><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=362220">Aaeorm</a>, Enchantement Technician of the Fortieth Tier of Xev.<li>Proud member of <A HREF="http://www.devotionguild.com">Devotion</a></ul></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
